API vs Web Services — Simple Interview Breakdown
1. Definition

API (Application Programming Interface)
A set of rules that allows one software to interact with another.

Web Service
A type of API that works only over the network, typically using HTTP.

2. Relation

All Web Services are APIs

But NOT all APIs are Web Services

Example:
Java Collections API, JDBC API → APIs but NOT Web Services.

3. Communication

API → Can work:

Within same machine

Across network

Between modules/classes

Web Service → MUST use a network (HTTP, SOAP, XML-RPC).

4. Data Format

API → Can use JSON, XML, binary, anything

Web Service → Traditionally XML (SOAP), modern ones can be JSON (REST)

5. Protocols

API → Any protocol or none

Web Service → Must use web-based protocols

HTTP

SOAP

REST

6. Examples

API Examples

JDBC API

Chrome Extension API

Java String API

Facebook Graph API (also web service)

Web Service Examples

SOAP Web Service

REST Web Service

Weather API over HTTP

⭐ One-Liner Difference (Most important)

API is a broad concept of enabling communication between software components.
Web service is a specific kind of API that communicates over the web using HTTP/SOAP.

⭐ 10-Second Interview Answer

APIs may or may not use the internet.
Web services must use the internet.
All web services are APIs, but all APIs are not web services.